3. What is the average price of all the vehicles? the median price? and the deciles? Displays these on a plot of the distribution of vehicle prices.

Information found on Piazza.

c <- vposts$price #assign vposts$price to c
mean_price = mean(c, na.rm = TRUE) #mean
mean_price
## [1] 49449.9
median_price = median(c, na.rm = TRUE) #median
median_price
## [1] 6700
quant_price = quantile(c, prob = seq(0, 1, .1), na.rm = TRUE) #decile
quant_price
##        0%       10%       20%       30%       40%       50%       60%

There are an extreme outliers that are skewing the distribution right. In statistics, an outlier is an observation point that is distant from other observations.

head(sort(vposts$price, decreasing = TRUE)) #look for outliers

There are 4 outliers and they are 600030000, 600030000, 30002500, and 9999999. Removing the outliers will allow me to be able to produce a graph that gives up a better representation of the data that we have.

5. Display the relationship between fuel type and vehicle type. Does this depend on transmission type?

levels(vposts$transmission)
## [1] "automatic" "manual"    "other"
bytrans = split(vposts, vposts$transmission)
by_trans_table = lapply(bytrans, function(d) table(d$fuel, d$type))

mosaicplot(by_trans_table$automatic, las = 2, main = 
      "5. Automatic: Type of Vehicle vs Fuel Type for Automatic", xlab = "Fuel Type",
      ylab = "Vehicle Type") #Shows the relationship between vehicle type vs fuel type for automatic. transmission

For automatic transmission, gass is the most common fuel type and truck is the most common vehicle type.

mosaicplot(by_trans_table$manual, las = 2, main = 
      "5. Manuel: Type of Fuel vs Transmission", xlab = "Fuel Type",
      ylab = "Vehicle Type") #Shows the relationship between fuel type vs fuel for manual.

For manual transmission, the most common fuel type is gas and the most common vehicle type is truck.

mosaicplot(by_trans_table$other, las = 2, main = "5. Other: Vehicle Type vs Fuel for Other",
      xlab = "Fuel Type", ylab = "Vehicle Type") #shows the relationship between type vs fuel for other.

For other transmission, the most common fuel type is gas and the most common vehicle type is truck.

Overall, it does not depend on transmission type because the most common fuel type and vehicle type are the same for all 3 types of transmission.

9. What are the three most common makes of cars in each city for sale by owner and for sale by dealer? Are they similar or quite different?

Corresponding with Chad Pickering

by_Owner <- subset(vposts, vposts$byOwner==TRUE) #vehicles sold by owner
by_Dealer <- subset(vposts, vposts$byOwner==FALSE) #vehicles sold by dealer

by_Owner_city_maker <- table(by_Owner$maker, by_Owner$city) #sold by owner x-axis = city, y-axis = maker
by_Dealer_city_maker <- table(by_Dealer$maker, by_Dealer$city) # sold by deaker, x-axis = city, y-axis = maker

top3_by_Owner <- function(x)
{
top3_in_order <- order(x, decreasing = TRUE)[1:3] #orders from highest to lowest, and then grabs the top 3
rownames(by_Owner_city_maker)[top3_in_order]
}

top3_by_Dealer <- function(x)
{
top3_in_order <- order(x, decreasing = TRUE)[1:3] #orders from highest to lowest, and then grabs the top 3
rownames(by_Dealer_city_maker)[top3_in_order]
}

The three most common makes of cars for each city that are sold by owner are:

#Lists the top 3 makers for each city by owner

by_Dealer <- subset(vposts, byOwner == FALSE)

      "10. Dist'n of Vehicle Age per City by Owner", 
      ylab="Frequency", ylim=c(0,40), las=2)

Since the distribution is extremely skewed to the right, it makes sense to zoom in on the boxplot to accurately see the distributions. After zooming in, we can see that the vehicles are between the ages 0 and 40. On average, NYC has the newest vehicles being sold by owner.

plot(by_Dealer$city, by_Dealer$ageOfVehicle, main = 
      "10. Dist'n of Vehicle Age per City by Dealer", ylab="Frequency", 
      ylim=c(0,25), las=2)

Similarly, since the distribution are skewed right, zooming in on the boxplots helps us see their distribution more accurately. The ages of the vehicles are between ages 0 and 25. On average, Sacramento has more older vehicles being sold by dealer.

library(lattice)

boxplot(condition_price[c(7, 8, 13, 10, 22)], condition_price, ylim = c(0, 35000),
      main = "16. Price of Vehichle vs Condition", xlab = "Condition", ylab = "Price")

Here, outliers were skewing distributions right and making the boxplot diffcult to see. After zooming in and ignoring the outliers, we are able to get a better view of the distributions. The prices of vehicles rage from $0 to $35000. The more expensive the car, better the condotion. Vehicles with the condition of fair were on aversage the cheapest.

condition_year = split(vposts$ageOfVehicle, vposts$condition)
boxplot(condition_year[c(7, 8, 13, 10, 22)], condition_price, ylim = c(0, 40), 
     main = "16. Age of Vehichle vs Condition", xlab = "Condidtion", ylab = "Age")

Zoomed in on the boxplots to get an accurate view of the distributions.The ages of the vehicles ranges from age 0 to 40. Vehicles with smaller ages were labeled with the condition of excellent or new. Vehicles labeled with the condotion fair have an older age on average.
